===Etymology===
From {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|μόλυβδος||lead}} and the suffix {{m|en|-mancy}}. Probably after Greek {{m|he|μολυβδομαντεία|tr=molybdomanteia}} or French {{m|fr|molybdomancie}}.<ref>[http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/molybdomancy Molybdomancy], Oxford Distionaries</ref>

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# [[divination|Divination]] by interpreting shapes formed when [[molten]] metal, typically [[lead]] or [[tin]], is dropped into water.
#* {{quote-journal|lang=en|1957|Robert Plank|Spontaneous Projection of Meaningful Forms|Journal of Projective Techniques|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Jr6zAAAAIAAJ&q=molybdomancy|page=146
|passage=The place of '''molybdomancy''' is also to be located in the uncertain border area between spontaneous and solicited projection.}}
#* {{quote-journal|lang=en|year=1971|month=January|author=Tak Hallus|title=Homage|work=Analog Science Fiction / Science Fact|page=67|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iOJZAAAAMAAJ
|passage=There was a happy group in Tallahassee swapping wives on the basis of '''molybdomancy'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|2003|[[w:Raymond Buckland|Raymond Buckland]]|The Fortune-Telling Book|page=199|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9RwdcbWJVcUC
|passage=Dropping hot lead or tin into water was another method occasionally employed by the Etruscans in a version of '''molybdomancy''', much like ceromancy.}}

